R crash course

This is an R crash couse, adpated and revised based on an online tutorial.

Let’s firstly setup a working directory

rr knitr::opts_knit$set(root.dir=/home/spr19/Desktop/PHC7065SPR2019/WK2)

We can assign objects using “<-”

rr foo <- world!
foo

[1] \hello world!\

R is case-sensitive

rr myvar <- 1 Myvar

Error: object 'Myvar' not found

We can add comments by using “#”

rr #foo2 <- world!
foo2

Error: object 'foo2' not found

Data structures:

Let’s look at vector first, which can be defined using c()

rr x <- c(1,2,3,4,5) x

[1] 1 2 3 4 5

rr firstNames <- c(,,,) firstNames

[1] \Shinji\ \Aska\   \Rey\    \Misato\

We can access the different parts of the vector using index: [idx]

rr firstNames[3]

[1] \Rey\

str() will allow us to explore the structure of a vector

rr str(firstNames)

 chr [1:4] \Shinji\ \Aska\ \Rey\ \Misato\

R treat categorical variables as factors. We can define that by using as.factor()

rr gender <- c(,,) gender <- as.factor(gender) str(gender)

 Factor w/ 2 levels \f\,\m\: 1 1 1 2 2 2

List is another data structure in R, which is a sequence of elements of different types

rr myList <- list(x=x,firstNames=firstNames,gender=gender) myList

$x
[1] 1 2 3 4 5

$firstNames
[1] \Shinji\ \Aska\   \Rey\    \Misato\

$gender
[1] f f f m m m
Levels: f m

We can access specific elements within the list

rr myList[[1]]

[1] 1 2 3 4 5

rr myList$x

[1] 1 2 3 4 5

rr myList[[]]

[1] 1 2 3 4 5

Now let’s move on to data frames

rr franchise <- c(, , , , ) city <- c(York, ```

We can get names of variables using colnames()

rr colnames(teams)

[1] \franchise\ \city\

Let’s write our first function: mean calculation

rr our.mean <- function(x){ return(sum(x) / length(x)) }

Let’s run the function on some data

rr x <- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5) x

[1] 1 2 3 4 5

rr our.mean(x) #self-defined mean

[1] 3

We can compare it with the built-in mean function

rr mean(x) #built-in mean

[1] 3

rr mean(x) == our.mean(x) #check whether these two values are equivalent

[1] TRUE

A more complex function

rr our.summary <- function(x) { mean <- mean(x) median <- median(x) standard_deviation <- sd(x) foo <- cbind(mean, median, standard_deviation) return(foo) } our.summary(x)

     mean median standard_deviation
[1,]    3      3           1.581139
